+# i915 checkpoint/restore capability map and contract
+
+## Scope and target
+
+This document defines the first hardware target and the state contract for
+checkpointing an i915 physical Wayland compositor. It intentionally separates
+state that current userspace APIs can observe from state that requires a new
+kernel checkpoint interface.
+
+The initial target captured on 2026-07-11 is:
+
+| Component | Value |
+| --- | --- |
+| Machine | Framework laptop |
+| PCI device | `0000:00:02.0`, Intel TigerLake-LP GT2 Iris Xe |
+| PCI IDs | vendor `8086`, device `9a49`, revision `01` |
+| Subsystem | Framework `f111:0001` |
+| Kernel | NixOS Linux `7.1.3`, PREEMPT_DYNAMIC |
+| Driver | `i915` (the device also advertises `xe` as an available module) |
+| DRM primary node | `/dev/dri/card1` |
+| Render node used by Niri | `/dev/dri/renderD128` |
+| CRIU baseline | 4.2, source commit `3c7d4fa01` |
+| Niri | 26.04 (Nixpkgs plus downstream patches) |
+| Mesa | Niri links `mesa-libgbm-26.0.3`; the active DRI GBM module is from Mesa 26.1.4 |
+| libdrm | 2.4.133 |
+| Session owner | authenticated UID 1000 |
+| Namespace layout | supervisor init PID 1, Niri PID 2 |
+| Persistent state | `/var/lib/wayland-session-supervisor/sessions/default` |
+
+The privileged target inventory recorded automatic-policy values (`-1`) for
+`enable_guc`, `enable_fbc`, `enable_psr`, and `enable_dc`, reset mode `3`, and
+enabled error capture. The kernel initialization log resolves the effective
+GuC state as disabled (`submission:no huc:no slpc:no`). The target has display
+version 12.00 stepping C0, a 4096 MiB GGTT, a 256 MiB GMADR aperture, system and
+stolen-system memory regions, and uses legacy `EXECBUFFER2_WR` submission rather
+than an observed VM_BIND path. Every hardware run must record the parameters
+and effective firmware/submission state because `-1` is policy, not a stable
+feature value.
+
+The kernel enables checkpoint/restore, modular i915, i915 error capture,
+i915 userptr, and modular xe. Debugfs was not mounted during collection; it
+remains optional diagnostic evidence and must not become a checkpoint ABI.
+
+## Reproduced failure
+
+An orderly physical reboot reaches Niri's first GEM mapping and fails before a
+checkpoint can be completed:
+
+```text
+Error (criu/proc_parse.c:502): Unknown shit 600 (anon_inode:i915.gem)
+Error (criu/proc_parse.c:738): Can't open 243977's mapfile link ...: No such device or address
+Error (criu/cr-dump.c:1587): Collect mappings (pid: 243977) failed with -1
+Error (criu/cr-dump.c:2128): Dumping FAILED.
+```
+
+`criu/proc_parse.c:vma_get_mapfile()` opens `/proc/PID/map_files/START-END`.
+For an i915 GEM VMA the kernel returns `ENXIO`; `fstatat()` reports mode `0600`
+without a regular file type, and CRIU rejects the unknown mapping before
+`HANDLE_DEVICE_VMA` can handle it. Therefore plugin-only recognition using the
+current hook placement is insufficient even before i915 object serialization
+is considered.
+
+At one observed Niri capture point the process contained:
+
+- 26 `rw-s` `anon_inode:i915.gem` VMAs;
+- 8,429,568 bytes of CPU-mapped GEM address space;
+- 14 dma-buf file descriptors exported by i915;
+- 3 `anon_inode:sync_file` descriptors;
+- 5 descriptors referring to the same `/dev/dri/card1` DRM client.
+
+The DRM fdinfo identifies driver `i915`, client ID 3, PCI device
+`0000:00:02.0`, approximately 100 MiB total/resident system memory, shared
+objects, and render-engine accounting. It exposes aggregate accounting, not a
+restorable per-handle object graph.
+
+Kernel DRM ioctl tracing confirms that this is not a mapping-only workload.
+Niri actively uses GEM create/create-ext, mmap-offset, set-domain, tiling,
+userptr, madvise, context create/get/set, `EXECBUFFER2_WR`, PRIME import/export,
+binary syncobj create/wait/export/destroy, framebuffer creation, atomic KMS
+commits and property blobs, and DRM master. Consequently the target contract
+must cover GEM, contexts/submission, dma-buf, synchronization, and KMS; none can
+be deferred while claiming physical Niri support.
+
+## Relevant CRIU plugin surfaces
+
+CRIU 4.2 provides these relevant hooks in `criu/include/criu-plugin.h`:
+
+- `DUMP_EXT_FILE(fd, id)` and `RESTORE_EXT_FILE(id)`;
+- `HANDLE_DEVICE_VMA(fd, stat)`;
+- `UPDATE_VMA_MAP(path, addr, old_pgoff, new_pgoff, plugin_fd)`;
+- `PAUSE_DEVICES(pid)` and `CHECKPOINT_DEVICES(pid)`;
+- `RESUME_DEVICES_LATE(pid)`;
+- `POST_FORKING()`.
+
+The AMDGPU plugin demonstrates the required lifecycle shape: identify device
+VMAs, drain target device descriptors, checkpoint kernel-managed state, create
+replacement files and objects, translate mmap offsets, restore VMAs, and only
+then resume device execution. It is a structural reference, not a compatible
+implementation. i915 rendering uses different object, VM, context, submission,
+and display models. The plugins can be loaded together, so each external-file
+hook must establish driver ownership before requiring driver-specific companion
+devices or topology. In particular, the AMDGPU hook queries the DRM driver name
+and returns `-ENOTSUP` for i915 file descriptions before consulting `/dev/kfd`;
+plugin ordering must never turn another driver's fd into a fatal dependency.
+For an i915 character fd on which `DRM_IOCTL_VERSION` is unavailable during
+CRIU file draining, ownership may fall back only to its immutable `st_rdev`
+entry under `/sys/dev/char`, whose resolved device-driver basename must be
+exactly `i915`; the subsequent transactional ioctl remains authoritative for
+authorization and supported state.
+
+A CRIU core change is required to let a plugin claim an `ENXIO` map-file entry
+before the generic unknown-map rejection. The revised interface must provide
+at least the target PID, VMA range, original page offset, map name, stat
+metadata, and a way to associate the VMA with a drained DRM file/object. Merely
+ignoring the mapping is forbidden.
+
+## Current i915 userspace capabilities
+
+The current i915 UAPI can create and operate on state when the caller already
+knows private identifiers:
+
+- `GEM_CREATE`/`GEM_CREATE_EXT` create buffer objects;
+- `GEM_MMAP_OFFSET`, `GEM_MMAP`, and `GEM_MMAP_GTT` create CPU mappings;
+- `GEM_PREAD`/`PWRITE` and mmap can transfer supported object contents;
+- `GEM_GET_TILING`, `GET_CACHING`, and related calls query selected properties
+  for a known GEM handle;
+- `GEM_WAIT`, `GEM_BUSY`, and `GEM_THROTTLE` help quiesce known work;
+- PRIME ioctls export/import known GEM handles as dma-buf fds;
+- context create/getparam/setparam APIs operate on known context IDs;
+- VM create/destroy and context VM parameters operate on known VM IDs;
+- `I915_QUERY` describes device topology, engines, and memory regions;
+- generic DRM syncobj APIs create, wait, signal, export, and import known
+  syncobj handles;
+- generic KMS APIs enumerate global connectors, CRTCs, planes, properties,
+  blobs, framebuffers, leases, and atomic state subject to DRM permissions.
+
+These APIs are useful for recreation but do not provide a complete checkpoint
+inventory.
+
+## State that cannot currently be enumerated or recreated exactly
+
+### GEM handle table and objects
+
+GEM handles are private to a `drm_file`. Current i915 UAPI has no operation to
+enumerate every handle and return a stable object identity, size, creation
+extensions/memory regions, tiling/modifier, cache/coherency state, madvise and
+purge state, mmap offsets, dma-buf relationships, pinning, and all mappings.
+
+A plugin cannot derive this graph from `/proc/PID/maps`:
+
+- not every GEM object must be CPU mapped;
+- one object may have multiple mappings;
+- map-file links cannot be opened for the observed i915 VMAs;
+- mmap offsets do not map back to private handles through public UAPI;
+- dma-buf fdinfo exposes exporter, size, inode, and reference count but not the
+  importing/exporting handle graph needed for exact recreation.
+
+### Contexts, engines, and GPU virtual memory
+
+Context parameter ioctls require known context IDs. There is no complete
+per-`drm_file` context enumeration API that exposes all engines, VM bindings,
+priorities, recoverability, persistence, SSEU, protected state, and submission
+state. VM IDs and object bindings likewise cannot be fully enumerated through
+current public i915 UAPI.
+
+Tiger Lake commonly uses legacy execbuffer/context VM behavior rather than the
+new xe model. The implementation must record the actual driver mode instead of
+assuming VM_BIND semantics.
+
+### Work queues and quiescence
+
+Waiting on a known object is insufficient to prove the entire client idle.
+Checkpoint requires an atomic client-level transition that blocks new
+submission, drains or preempts all requests, reports unsupported active state,
+and holds the client frozen until checkpoint completion or rollback. Ptrace
+stopping userspace prevents new ioctls but does not itself serialize or prove
+all GPU requests and kernel callbacks quiescent.
+
+### Synchronization
+
+Generic syncobj operations require known handles and do not enumerate a
+client's syncobj handle table or all timeline points. `sync_file` descriptors
+and dma-buf reservation fences also require identity-preserving relationship
+reconstruction. Restoring only signaled/unsignaled booleans is not sufficient
+for timeline or shared-fence semantics.
+
+### KMS and DRM ownership
+
+Global KMS resources are queryable, but exact restore also needs the target
+client's DRM master/lease ownership, framebuffer-to-GEM relationships, atomic
+property/blob state, event delivery, pending flips/commits, and safe reacquire
+ordering after reboot. Active or pending commits must be drained or refused.
+DRM master must not be exposed before authenticated restore.
+
+## Kernel interface is required
+
+For transparent checkpoint of an arbitrary existing Niri process, a new i915
+kernel checkpoint/restore ABI is required. LD_PRELOAD ioctl tracking, Mesa
+structure inspection, or application cooperation would not cover arbitrary
+existing state and would violate the transparent exact-restoration contract.
+Debugfs is diagnostic, privileged, unstable, and not a restore ABI.
+
+The minimum kernel-side design must provide an authorized operation scoped to
+a drained target `drm_file` that:
+
+1. atomically freezes new client submissions and quiesces all engines;
+2. enumerates a versioned object graph for that DRM client;
+3. assigns checkpoint-local stable IDs independent of GEM handles and global
+   mmap offsets;
+4. reports every GEM object, object property, handle alias, VMA/mmap offset,
+   dma-buf relationship, context, engine set, VM, binding, syncobj/timeline,
+   fence dependency, and KMS-owned object required for exact restore;
+5. permits coherent extraction of supported object contents;
+6. explicitly labels unsupported, protected, external, lost, purged, active,
+   or generation-specific state;
+7. holds or cleanly rolls back the frozen state until CRIU completes;
+8. recreates a validated graph on a compatible device and returns translated
+   handles, mmap offsets, context/VM IDs, and plugin-visible mappings;
+9. defers GPU execution and userptr/MMU-notifier activation until CRIU has
+   restored CPU VMAs;
+10. enforces ptrace-equivalent dump authorization and privileged, fully
+    validated restore authorization.
+
+The ABI must be versioned and extensible. It must not ingest raw privileged
+hardware command/state blobs without strict validation. Cross-device restore
+is refused unless device identity and a separately reviewed compatibility
+contract permit it.
+
+## Proposed checkpoint image graph
+
+The plugin image should use checkpoint-local IDs and contain, at minimum:
+
+- **device**: PCI identity, driver (`i915`), generation/platform, topology,
+  memory regions, page sizes, firmware/submission mode, reset epoch, required
+  UAPI/kernel checkpoint feature bits;
+- **DRM file**: CRIU file ID, node role, client capabilities, authentication,
+  master/lease identity, and object/context/sync handle aliases;
+- **GEM object**: stable object ID, size, regions, flags/extensions,
+  tiling/modifier/stride where applicable, cache/coherency properties,
+  purge/advice state, content image and hash;
+- **CPU VMA**: process, address range, protection/flags, object ID, object
+  offset, original mmap type and translated restore offset;
+- **dma-buf edge**: exporter object, importer DRM file/handle, fd identity,
+  access mode, reservation/fence relationships, and external-peer status;
+- **context/VM**: context properties, engine map, VM identity, object bindings,
+  addresses, permissions, and recoverability;
+- **synchronization**: syncobj aliases, timeline points, sync_file and fence
+  graph, signaled/error state, and object reservations;
+- **KMS state**: owned framebuffer/GEM references, leases, selected atomic
+  properties/blobs, and a declaration that no unsupported pending commit exists;
+- **compatibility**: schema, CRIU plugin version, kernel ABI version and
+  required feature bits.
+
+Object contents belong in separately hashed images so corruption and excessive
+sensitive-data exposure can be handled conservatively.
+
+## Restore order
+
+1. Authenticate the original session owner.
+2. Verify device and kernel/plugin compatibility before creating process state.
+3. Open the correct primary/render nodes and acquire permitted DRM ownership.
+4. Ask the kernel restore ABI to create a suspended DRM client graph.
+5. Recreate GEM objects, aliases, dma-buf sharing, contexts, VMs, bindings, and
+   sync state; obtain translated mmap offsets and plugin fds.
+6. Let CRIU restore CPU VMAs at their original virtual addresses using
+   `UPDATE_VMA_MAP` translations.
+7. Restore process file descriptors and KMS ownership/state while display
+   exposure remains gated.
+8. After all process VMAs and MMU notifiers exist, validate the complete graph.
+9. Resume GPU execution and atomic display commits with
+   `RESUME_DEVICES_LATE`.
+10. Publish restore success only after post-restore GPU and KMS health checks.
+
+Any failure before step 10 tears down the partial graph and leaves the greeter
+in control.
+
+## Explicit refusal cases for the first version
+
+The first version must refuse, with structured diagnostics:
+
+- a different PCI device, driver, generation, or required feature set;
+- protected/encrypted objects or contexts;
+- unrecoverable/lost contexts or a GPU reset during checkpoint;
+- unquiesceable requests or pending KMS commits;
+- unsupported userptr, sparse, or generation-specific binding state;
+- dma-buf or sync dependencies on indispensable peers outside the managed
+  process domain;
+- purged objects whose exact contents cannot be recovered;
+- image corruption or unknown schema/kernel ABI features;
+- restore without required authentication and privilege.
+
+## Minimal implementation boundary
+
+The first executable milestone is deliberately narrower than Niri:
+
+1. one DRM render-node file;
+2. one i915 GEM object created with the ordinary create UAPI;
+3. one shared CPU mapping with deterministic contents;
+4. no external dma-buf peer, protected content, active request, KMS object, or
+   non-default context;
+5. dump through the new CRIU ENXIO-VMA path and kernel inventory ABI;
+6. recreate the object, translate its mmap offset, map it at the original CPU
+   address, verify its hash, and perform a new supported GPU operation.
+
+This milestone still requires the kernel to expose object identity and restore
+mapping because current UAPI cannot map an observed `anon_inode:i915.gem` VMA
+back to its private handle transparently.
+
+### Minimal milestone verification
+
+On 2026-07-12, `test/others/i915-criu/run-minimal-criu.sh` passed on the target
+recorded in `test/others/i915-target-framework.json`. The root CRIU 4.2 run:
+
+- dumped an `anon_inode:i915.gem` VMA through the i915 plugin and v1 kernel
+  transaction;
+- restored the original PID and virtual address with bit-identical deterministic
+  contents;
+- performed post-restore CPU domain access, `EXECBUFFER2`, and `GEM_WAIT`;
+- rejected a v2 image-header version and a truncated object payload; and
+- observed no surviving partially restored fixture after either refusal.
+
+The test uses an explicit plugin directory so it cannot accidentally pass
+without loading `i915_plugin.so`. This is evidence only for the deliberately
+minimal boundary above, not for sharing, mutable contexts, synchronization,
+KMS, Niri, reboot, or production safety.
+
+### Sharing expansion baseline
+
+`test/others/i915-criu/i915-gem-sharing.c` creates one object, exports it as a
+dma-buf, imports it into a separately opened i915 file in a child process, and
+maps it in both processes. Its uncheckpointed control run proves bidirectional
+CPU visibility and a subsequent parent `EXECBUFFER2`/`GEM_WAIT`. The matching
+`run-sharing-criu.sh` currently expects exact restoration once sharing support
+is implemented.
+
+On the minimal v1 ABI, `I915_CRIU_EXPECT_UNSUPPORTED=1` instead verifies that
+the shared-object query causes an ordinary CRIU dump refusal. This regression
+also covers an earlier plugin cleanup bug where refusal before the first object
+allocation dereferenced a nonexistent dump object and terminated CRIU with
+`SIGSEGV`. The unsupported baseline must remain fail-closed while the sharing
+transaction is developed.
+
+The current sharing transaction keeps one opaque kernel-assigned object ID on
+each i915 GEM object, so every handle in independently opened i915 files emits
+the same image identity without exposing a kernel pointer. CRIU's
+`FINALIZE_DEVICES` hook runs only after every task's file table is dumped and
+refuses the checkpoint unless the number of captured handles for each object
+exactly matches the driver's handle count. Restore creates the object once,
+uses PRIME import to recreate subsequent private handles, compares duplicate
+payloads, and delays every per-file transaction commit until all required
+handles and mappings exist. The plugin opts into CRIU's `PREPARE_RESTORE` hook,
+scans its private image names in the master before task forking, and stores both
+transaction and external-file descriptors in CRIU's shared fdstore. Restored
+tasks receive temporary fdstore copies, so plugin-owned descriptors cannot
+collide with target fd numbers and every task inherits one shared object graph.
+
+On 2026-07-12 the physical two-process test restored parent PID 30773 and child
+PID 30775 at their original `0x7e791ee99000` and `0x7e791ee95000` mappings. A
+child write was immediately visible through the parent's mapping, after which
+the parent completed `EXECBUFFER2` and `GEM_WAIT`. The external-peer mode also
+refused dump finalization after reporting one captured handle while two existed.
+
+`I915_CRIU_EXTERNAL_PEER=1 run-sharing-criu.sh` reparents the importing peer
+outside the captured tree and requires the finalize hook to refuse the missing
+handle before dump completion.
+
+ABI and private image version 6 add independently retained i915-exported
+dma-buf file descriptions. CRIU invokes a plugin reference hook for every fd,
+including duplicate descriptors, while retaining one image per shared file
+description. At finalization, after CRIU closes its temporary drained-fd
+copies, the plugin re-queries each object through an authorized captured DRM
+file. Admission requires the kernel dma-buf refcount to equal the exporter
+cache reference, every proven i915 handle relationship, and every captured
+dma-buf fd. Attachments and imported non-i915 objects remain refused. This
+catches an external process retaining only the dma-buf fd even when all GEM
+handles are inside the captured domain.
+
+`i915-gem-sharing --retained-dmabuf` keeps two duplicate descriptors live and
+validates their restored object identity. `--external-dmabuf-peer` reparents a
+process that holds only the exported fd and requires finalization refusal.
+On 2026-07-14, the ABI/image version 6 physical suite restored the retained
+file description with duplicate descriptors and refused the reparented
+external dma-buf-only holder before dump completion. The retained mode-0700
+evidence is `/var/tmp/i915-criu-physical-20260714T000559Z`; handle equality
+alone is not treated as sufficient evidence.
+
+### Synchronization expansion
+
+ABI and private image version 6 (building on version 3 synchronization,
+version 4 idle-context support, and version 5 GPU bindings) enumerate each DRM
+file's syncobj handle table
+inside the authorized dump transaction. The supported subset is deliberately
+limited to empty syncobjs, signaled binary syncobjs, and timeline syncobjs whose
+latest submitted point is fully signaled. Restore creates the handles in their
+original order through the transaction, requires exact handle values, and
+re-signals the recorded timeline point before commit. Abort removes both GEM
+and syncobj handles created by the transaction.
+
+Dump refuses unsignaled fences, registered callbacks/eventfds, and syncobj
+file-description exports. GEM reservation fences receive a bounded five-second
+quiescence wait; a request that cannot finish is refused instead of hanging the
+checkpoint indefinitely. This treats any remaining in-flight or externally
+referenced fence graph as unsupported rather than converting it to a completed
+fence.
+
+ABI and private image version 7 add the narrower `sync_file` relationship that
+can be proved exactly: a successful signaled binary fence exported from one
+unambiguous captured i915 syncobj. A driver query accepts the candidate
+`sync_file` fd only inside an authorized dump transaction, verifies successful
+signaled state, matches the exact fence to one syncobj handle, and reports the
+complete file refcount excluding its own temporary lookup. CRIU counts every
+captured duplicate fd and retains one private plugin reference through final
+graph validation, so an external process or other uncaptured file holder causes
+explicit refusal. Restore recreates the syncobj first, then asks the same active
+restore transaction to export a new `sync_file` backed by that restored fence;
+duplicate target descriptors continue to share one CRIU external-file identity.
+Timeline exports, merged fences, error fences, implicit reservation fences with
+no captured syncobj source, ambiguous syncobj aliases, and syncobj-file exports
+remain unsupported. On 2026-07-14, the ABI/image version 7 physical suite
+restored the retained duplicate descriptors, verified both as signaled and
+importable into new syncobjs, completed a new GPU submission, and refused a
+reparented external `sync_file`-only holder before dump completion.
+
+The
+`i915-context-sync.c --sync-only` mode isolates binary/timeline coverage from
+custom-context and explicit-VM state and performs its first GPU submission only
+after resume. Its uncheckpointed control passes; physical CRIU proof requires
+booting the matching kernel/plugin. `--callback` registers an eventfd
+waiter on its empty binary syncobj and requires dump admission to return a
+normal refusal; the fixture treats any resume as failure.
+
+Version 4 introduced dense explicit VM and proto-context ID tables. It
+preserves context priority, bannable/recoverable/persistence/error-capture
+flags, optional single-timeline mode, and the context-to-VM relationship. Only
+configured contexts that have never submitted and VMs with no bound or unbound
+VMA are admitted. The default context is likewise refused if its VM contains
+any user binding, preventing an earlier submission from being mistaken for the
+minimal idle state. Restore recreates exact IDs through the privileged
+transaction and abort removes contexts before their VMs. `--idle-context` exercises this
+narrow stage and requires a new post-restore submission through the recreated
+context and VM.
+
+Version 5 admits idle materialized contexts only when they use the default
+engine map and have no active engine. It inventories each ordinary local VMA
+binding by VM ID, opaque object ID, size, and exact GPU virtual address. Restore
+recreates the binding through validated i915 VMA APIs before transaction commit;
+the fixture resubmits with `EXEC_OBJECT_PINNED` and requires the original GPU
+address, including valid address zero. Custom engine maps, active requests,
+special views, scanout/fenced/userfault/global bindings, and inaccessible
+objects remain refused.
+
+On 2026-07-13 the version-4 suite passed minimal GEM and corruption, shared GEM,
+external-peer refusal, binary/timeline synchronization, callback refusal, idle
+context/VM restoration, and submitted-context refusal. The retained evidence is
+`/var/tmp/i915-criu-abi4-20260713T122717Z`.
+
+On 2026-07-13 ABI/image version 5 passed all nine staged cases on the Framework
+target. The retained mode-0700 evidence is
+`/var/tmp/i915-criu-physical-20260713T183559Z`: minimal GEM plus incompatible
+schema and truncation negatives; shared GEM positive; external-peer and
+retained-dma-buf negatives; binary/timeline syncobj positive; callback refusal;
+idle context/VM positive; materialized context/VM/exact-GPU-address positive;
+and custom-engine refusal. The materialized-context fixture submitted before
+capture, restored GPU address zero as a valid exact binding, then completed a
+new pinned-address submission and bounded GEM wait after restore.
+
+On 2026-07-14 ABI/image version 6 passed all ten staged cases on the same
+Framework target and boot generation
+`/nix/store/xkqqckmcagzi7m4ps9sx1p4fyd2xp9xs-nixos-system-framie-26.05.20260709.5fe3335`.
+The retained evidence is `/var/tmp/i915-criu-physical-20260714T000559Z`.
+In addition to the version-5 coverage, it proves restoration of one retained
+exported dma-buf file description with duplicate fds and fail-closed refusal of
+a reparented process retaining only that dma-buf fd. The exact-address case
+again reached `SUBMITTED` and `QUIESCED` after restore and passed a new pinned
+GPU submission.
+
+On 2026-07-14 ABI/image version 7 passed all twelve staged cases. The retained
+mode-0700 evidence is `/var/tmp/i915-criu-physical-20260714T023744Z`, captured
+on boot ID `9278e8b8-8ec4-4bd2-a245-0109c9feda7d` with the matching kernel,
+plugin, and image schema. It adds the retained binary `sync_file` positive and
+external-holder negative while retaining all GEM, dma-buf, context/VM,
+exact-address submission, syncobj/timeline, corruption, callback, and custom
+engine results.
+
+### Physical KMS expansion
+
+ABI and private image version 8 added an explicitly bounded first physical-KMS
+stage. `DRM_IOCTL_I915_CRIU_FILE` records the primary/render node role, client
+capabilities, authentication state, and current DRM-master ownership. Dump and
+restore refuse pending or unread DRM events and DRM leases rather than dropping
+them. Restore opens the matching node, reacquires master only after the
+privileged restore phase has begun, reapplies the recorded client capabilities,
+and requires the resulting file state to match exactly.
+
+The file-state record also carries the PCI vendor/device, subsystem IDs, and
+revision. Restore obtains those values from the newly opened kernel device and
+rejects a mismatch before object creation. Each dump and restore transaction
+snapshots i915's global GPU reset counter; every subsequent operation and commit
+returns `EIO` if a reset occurred while the graph was being serialized or
+created.
+
+The same transaction enumerates file-owned framebuffer IDs and property-blob
+IDs. DRM core takes one internal GEM `handle_count` reference for each
+framebuffer plane without adding an entry to any userspace handle table; ABI 8
+subtracts those proven framebuffer-only references before CRIU performs its
+complete userspace-handle graph check. It does not weaken external-handle
+refusal. This first admission subset is one-plane linear XRGB8888 framebuffers
+backed by already captured local i915 shmem objects and bounded user property
+blobs. Restore recreates both through validated DRM/i915 constructors and
+atomically assigns their exact userspace-visible mode-object IDs; conflicts or
+incompatible display capabilities fail before resume. Multi-planar or tiled
+framebuffers, imported objects, leases, pending flips/events, and inaccessible
+blob graphs remain unsupported.
+
+ABI and private image version 9 make CPU mapping provenance explicit. The
+physical ABI-8 run at
+`/var/tmp/i915-criu-physical-20260714T154548Z` successfully recreated the KMS
+objects and reached process restoration, but the first dumb-buffer VMA failed
+with `EACCES`: `MODE_MAP_DUMB` had created a WC mmap-offset node while object
+inventory had recorded a separate WB node. Reusing the captured WC offset or a
+newly opened DRM fd is neither exact nor authorized.
+`DRM_IOCTL_I915_CRIU_MAPPING` now resolves every captured `i915.gem` VMA offset
+inside the authorized dump transaction to its opaque object, mmap type, node
+base, and bounded size. The image records each distinct node. Restore recreates
+the same type through the object-owning DRM file and translates base plus
+subrange delta; an unresolved, overlapping, unauthorized, fixed/special, or
+corrupt mapping refuses the transaction. CRIU no longer falls back to reopening
+a DRM path when an i915 mapping record is absent.
+
+The first ABI-9 KMS attempt also exposed a CRIU VMA-inventory issue: adjacent
+mappings with equal anonymous-device inode metadata borrowed one file-info
+record, so only the first VMA reached the plugin. File identity remains safely
+shared, but CRIU now invokes the anonymous-device hook for every borrowed VMA
+so device-private mmap-offset provenance cannot collapse. The focused physical
+rerun at `/var/tmp/i915-kms-abi9-adjacent` recorded both WC nodes, restored both
+VMAs at their original virtual addresses with bit-identical contents, retained
+DRM master and exact framebuffer/blob IDs, restored atomic scanout, and consumed
+a real post-restore page-flip event. Its image has two object and two mapping
+records; `images/restore.log` ends in `Restore finished successfully`.
+
+The plugin records mutable atomic properties only for the active connector,
+CRTC, and planes, excluding immutable, legacy DPMS, and transient fence-pointer
+properties. It verifies every restored object/property ID, submits a full
+`DRM_MODE_ATOMIC_TEST_ONLY | DRM_MODE_ATOMIC_ALLOW_MODESET` transaction, then
+issues the real atomic modeset while the i915 restore transaction is still
+active. Non-master DRM files commit first and the KMS master commits last, so a
+reset or commit failure can still abort the master transaction, remove its
+recreated framebuffers/blobs, and disable the restored scanout before any
+process resumes. An atomic failure is a restore failure;
+there is no partial-success path.
+
+`i915-kms-atomic.c` creates two deterministic dumb-buffer framebuffers, an exact
+mode blob, and an active atomic eDP pipeline while holding DRM master. After
+restore it requires the same master file description, blob/framebuffer IDs,
+scanout properties, and bit-identical mappings, then switches to the second
+restored framebuffer and consumes a real page-flip event. The matching
+`run-kms-criu.sh` must run from a text console with the graphical session
+stopped. ABI-9 implementation and warning-clean kernel/plugin/fixture builds
+must complete before physical pass evidence is claimed. The KMS harness also corrupts captured PCI identity to prove incompatible-device
+refusal and uses i915's privileged debugfs reset injector during a deliberately
+paused test transaction to prove reset detection without admitting a partial
+image.
+
+`run-physical-suite.sh` reproduces all prior cases in one privileged run and,
+for ABI 9, adds the physical atomic-KMS case and mapping-count corruption
+refusal after the retained duplicate
+`sync_file` and external-holder cases. It must be launched from a text console
+with the graphical session stopped so the KMS fixture can acquire DRM master.
+It creates a private mode-0700 evidence directory containing per-case logs,
+kernel/boot/system/PCI/i915/CRIU/plugin/Niri metadata, and a machine-readable
+verdict. When invoked through sudo, an exit trap returns that directory to the
+invoking UID/GID without broadening its mode. Fixtures are compiled unprivileged
+beforehand and passed from `/tmp` by default, keeping the root run free of
+ad-hoc toolchain dependencies.
+
+On 2026-07-15 ABI/image version 9 passed all eighteen staged cases on boot ID
+`64fda6fe-15cf-40ea-ba14-cb8d09ecd709` and the final NixOS generation
+`/nix/store/bk4x1f27gbmm8cbfd1v35fpmp8s357f7-nixos-system-framie-26.05.20260709.5fe3335`.
+The private evidence directory is
+`/var/tmp/i915-criu-physical-final-20260715T132240Z`; both
+`verdict.json` and `invocation-status.txt` report success. Its positive KMS
+fixture retained DRM master, exact blob IDs `780`, framebuffer IDs `778` and
+`779`, both independent WC mapping records and bit-identical contents, active
+atomic eDP scanout, and delivery of a new page-flip event after restore. The
+negative matrix refused role, framebuffer-count, mapping-count, and PCI-device
+corruption transactionally, in addition to the earlier schema, sharing,
+dma-buf, sync-file, callback, and custom-engine refusal cases.
+
+ABI and private image version 10 narrow that historical custom-engine refusal
+to a reconstructible subset required by the physical Mesa iris client. A
+context may carry at most 64 ordered engine slots, each either the explicit
+invalid sentinel or one physical engine class/instance present on the target.
+The kernel refuses load-balanced, parallel, bonded, virtual, unknown, and
+per-engine SSEU state, and refuses any active engine before image creation.
+The image records every slot in order; restore validates the target engine
+identity and attaches the exact physical map to the proto-context before it can
+materialize. The staged suite turns the one-render-engine fixture into a
+positive exact-address/post-restore-submission case and adds a load-balanced
+virtual-engine negative. Physical Niri evidence at
+`/var/tmp/wss-physical-niri-admission-20260716T015424Z` established that its
+shared seatd/Niri primary-node description reaches the i915 transaction and is
+refused during ABI-9 begin validation; ABI-10 physical validation remains
+pending and must not be reported as compositor success.
+
+An idle i915 engine treats a debugfs reset request as a successful no-op, so the
+reset test now starts a separate render client only after the target dump
+transaction reaches its deliberate pause and keeps a long batch stream queued.
+This leaves target-client quiescence unchanged while guaranteeing that the
+request performs a real `rcs0` reset and advances the driver's reset epoch. The
+strengthened focused evidence at `/var/tmp/i915-kms-reset-real-final` records
+the `GPU HANG`, `Resetting rcs0 for Manually reset engine mask to 1`, and
+context-reset messages in `reset-kernel.log`. CRIU exits with status 1,
+`dump.log` ends in `Dumping FAILED`, and no complete inventory or i915 private
+image exists. The original KMS fixture then revalidates DRM master, exact
+framebuffer/blob identities, scanout properties and both mapped contents, and
+successfully consumes a new page-flip event. Thus reset interruption neither
+commits a partial checkpoint nor damages the existing display state.
+
+`generation-supplement.json` binds the full run to i915 module SHA-256
+`fb7001801215ee83adfee0c45a01d36334120e2e92d3acaa6969da5c0521e6a0`,
+plugin SHA-256
+`0344a43812b78b82db91e984826ea1d81510197db4fab20efd491d8855504996`,
+libdrm 2.4.133, Niri's Mesa libgbm 26.0.3, Mesa iris 26.1.4, and the four
+fixture hashes. The matching boot log resolves automatic GuC policy to
+`enable_guc=0 (guc:no submission:no huc:no slpc:no)`. This evidence completes
+the isolated physical-KMS boundary; it does not by itself establish physical
+Niri restoration, authenticated reboot restoration, repeated-cycle leak
+freedom, or production safety.
+
+### Physical Niri admission baseline
+
+The first isolated physical-Niri run on 2026-07-15 used the supervisor's real
+PID and mount namespaces with a minimal Niri configuration and no clients. The
+private cgroup and process tree were equal and contained exactly namespace init
+(PID 1) and Niri (PID 2). Niri acquired i915 render and primary nodes, DRM
+master, the Framework eDP panel, and both attached DisplayPort outputs. This
+establishes a useful compositor admission baseline, not a restore result.
+
+The first capture exposed two process-domain issues before i915 inventory could
+admit compositor state. First, the anonymous-VMA surrogate was opened in CRIU's
+mount namespace, whose devtmpfs mount ID did not exist in the target mount
+tree. Commit `549d10d60` opens the configured render node through
+`/proc/<target-pid>/root`; the physical rerun advanced past mount lookup with
+the target devtmpfs identity.
+
+Second, Niri retained a pidfd supplied by the host seat/session stack. Its
+target PID namespace is the host namespace rather than the supervised domain,
+so CRIU correctly refused it as outside the checkpoint tree. Rebinding that
+pidfd to a newly booted host process would be external-resource reconstruction,
+not exact restoration. The current exactness policy therefore requires either
+placing the seat authority and its process references inside the checkpoint
+domain or defining a separately reviewed exception; silently treating the host
+pidfd as namespace PID 1 is forbidden. No physical Niri success claim is made
+until this relationship and all subsequent GPU/KMS refusals are represented
+exactly.
+
+The ad-hoc baseline also took control of the active seat without a proven
+out-of-band escape. The prior-boot journal contains no kernel BUG, Oops, GPU
+hang, or lockup before the forced power-off; the failure is consistent with an
+unsafe test harness, not evidence of a kernel defect. Physical compositor tests
+must not be re-enabled until an independent systemd watchdog has been proven to
+terminate the transient scope, a non-inhibitable immediate quit binding is
+present, capture has a bounded timeout, and a remote/system control path has
+been tested before DRM/input acquisition.
+
+### Evdev boundary exposed by the physical compositor
+
+The bounded physical run at
+`/var/tmp/wss-physical-niri-admission-20260715T214728Z` reached CRIU with an
+exact four-process cgroup/tree: namespace init, `seatd-launch`, in-domain
+`seatd`, and physical Niri. Niri held i915 DRM master and active eDP-1, DP-5,
+and DP-7 scanout. CRIU then refused seatd's first evdev file description:
+`/dev/input/event2` (`chr 13:66`). This is a required exact-domain resource,
+not a descriptor to externalize or silently reopen.
+
+`EVIOCGCRIUSTATE` version 1 therefore provides conservative, read-only
+admission for one evdev file description. It reports the timestamp clock,
+buffer size, queue depth, and explicit flags for queued events, grabs,
+per-client filtering, and force-feedback capability. The initial input plugin
+admits only an empty, ungrabbed, unfiltered, non-force-feedback client. Its
+checksummed private image records complete input identity and capabilities,
+absolute-axis and multitouch-slot state, key/LED/sound/switch state, repeat
+settings, and the evdev clock. Restore scans event nodes rather than trusting
+an unstable event number, requires exactly one identity match, verifies global
+state exactly, recreates the admitted default-empty client, and rejects any
+event arriving before restore attachment. Queued events, grabs, masks,
+force-feedback effects, ambiguous devices, changed global state, corrupt
+images, and ABI mismatch remain explicit failures.
+
+This narrow subset is sufficient only after physical proof. It does not claim
+that arbitrary evdev clients are checkpointable, and it does not discard input
+arriving before dump admission. The uinput ABI fixture exercises malformed
+version/size/reserved fields plus queue, mask, grab, and clock reporting.
+
+The same run series diagnosed VT switching independently: `wev` records F2 as
+`XF86Switch_VT_2`, Niri invokes its hardcoded `ChangeVt(2)` path, and the
+production log reports `Failed to change vt: Permission denied`. The supervised
+compositor is no longer a process in logind's active session scope, so login1
+cannot authorize Niri's non-interactive switch request. Production must use the
+already-tested in-domain seat authority rather than weakening login1 policy.
+
+## Privileged evidence policy
+
+The initial root inventory now records module policy values, effective GuC
+state, reset/error-capture configuration, kernel feature configuration, memory
+regions, and the actual Niri ioctl surface. Future capture points should also
+retain reset stats and error state. If debugfs is already available, per-client
+GEM/context/engine reports may validate the model, but the test must not mount
+or depend on debugfs merely to make checkpointing work. These sources are
+unstable diagnostics, not a production checkpoint ABI.
